title: Charged-particle emission by 175 MeV proton on nickel targets

x4freetext: Charged-particle emission by 175 MeV proton on nickel
targets
To be submitted as the thesis of B.Piskor-Ignatowicz
to Jagellonian University, Krakow, Poland
COSY
Two methods gave normalization factors which agreed
with accuracy of about 20% what is quite good results
taking into account the fact of 10%  error of
normalization, quoted by Foertsch et al., inaccuracy
of total 7Be cross sections extracted from the
spectra, and the error of parameterization of Bubak
et al. This good agreement gives additional confidence
in the absolute normalization.
Absolute normalization of the data was done by
comparing double differential cross section of protons
measured by PISA experiment with the cross sections
published by Foertsch at al. in 1991.
In this paper the energy spectra of protons were
determined for many angles, i.e. from 15 to 70 degrees
in 5 degree steps and for 80, 90, 100, 120 degrees,
thus it was possible to compare  our data at several
angles (15, 20, 65 and 100 degrees) with those of
Foertsch et al. It was found that the shapes of all
compared spectra agree very well and, moreover, the
ratio of our data to those of Foertsch et al. is the
same for all angles. Therefore we normalized cross
sections for all products observed in our experiment
relying on the absolute normalization of proton data
found by Foertsch et al.
Normalization factor was found using method of the
weighted least squares for each angle separately and
then mean value of four angles were used as
normalization factor. The statistical error of
normalization factor was found to be close to 3%.
Additionally systematic error of data of Foertsch et
al. (as authors claimed it is close to 10%) should be
taken into consideration.
The second method of normalization was performed
independently. It consisted in comparing the
experimental total cross section for emission of 7Be
with results of parameterization of 7Be data published
in the literature of Bubak at al. This method is less
accurate as comparing proton spectra with results of
Foertsch et al. because of two reasons:
(1) Statistics of 7Be spectra in reaction Ni(p,7Be)
is much poorer than statistics of proton spectra,
(2) The experimental total cross sections should be
derived from the spectra by integration over angle
and energy what is biased with virtually large
error because the experimental spectra are not
measured at very low 7Be energies, where the cross
sections are relatively large.
